        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">PastorOfMuppets wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I try to make my design decisions based on the product constraints and the business needs and keep everything data driven. When arguing a position I stick to the facts and  present the data and method the decision was reached. Unfortunately when presented with overwhelming facts, the typical response has been to trash me behind my back to senior management.</div><br />To me, this stuck out like a sore thumb. Short version: <span style="font-weight: bold">being right isn't enough</span>.<br /><br />Longer version: All business/engineering decisions are personal, and you cannot defeat irrational behavior with overwhelming facts. Nobody likes being overwhelmed with anything, facts or otherwise. Nobody likes being told their idea is wrong. Some &quot;office politics&quot; is kind of like training a cat - you'll be most successful if you can convince the cat that it was their idea all along. <br /><br />More practically, you can use language to guide people. The goal is to <span style="font-style: italic">de-emphasize confrontation </span>and keep the focus where you want it - getting a solution to a problem. I try not to talk about &quot;my idea&quot; or &quot;your idea&quot;, but &quot;the FOO idea&quot; or &quot;the BAR idea&quot;. If I suspect BAR won't work, I prefer to ask leading questions like &quot;Can you show me how BAR will fill the BAZ requirement?&quot; rather than flatly stating &quot;BAR won't work (and here's why)&quot; Nobody wants to be &quot;educated&quot;. You don't want to &quot;win&quot; an argument. They might be wrong, but you want to give them a path to less-wrong that is as kind as possible to their ego. <br /><br />Remember: you use software engineering techniques to develop robust software, you use social engineering techniques to develop robust relationships with people  <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/razz.png" alt=":p" title="Razz" />

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
