          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">PastorOfMuppets wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So I start at a company work on a couple of projects have some successes and I am given more responsibility and bigger projects. Eventually a lead in another group will question my approach, because they have the &quot;one true way&quot;. </div><br />This part suggests to me that you're coming across as threatening to your peers, who have already established their relationships.  You're giving off a vibe not of trying to help the project succeed, but of trying to get other people pushed out of your way.  That's not a bad thing for the company if your way is actually right and they're actually wrong - if you can help highlight true incompetence and root it out, bully for you.  But as you've found, being right often isn't enough.  You have two choices:<br /><br />1) Offer solutions that don't threaten your peers, if it can be avoided.<br /><br />2) Anticipate possible objections, and come up with a proactive plan to mitigate them.  As dazd suggested, this might mean you &quot;socialize&quot; your idea up the org chart first before formally presenting it.  Present it with a pro/con analysis and how it will impact other areas.  Just show that you're thinking it through and not just charging ahead like a bull in a china shop, consequences be damned.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
