              <div class="quotetitle">Bagheera wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Hopers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Don't start asking people about their kids just because you need to tick something off on your &quot;I'm a good coworker&quot; checklist. </div><br /><br />I disagree. I think you should make an effort to be social even if you have no desire to do so. Personally, I don't care at all about my coworkers' kids or about who's getting traded in the NFL. But I still ask people how their kids are doing or what they think of the home team. My coworkers know full well I'm not interested in these topics, but they appreciate that I'm asking. <br /><br />Since I started doing this, people like me better and I get my way more often. I can see a clear causal connection between &quot;Will the Dolphins make the playoffs? Does your daughter still have the flu?&quot; and &quot;Thanks for accepting my project and supporting me with upper management.&quot;</div><br /><br />Sorry, I wasn't very clear. Whoops!<br /><br />I think that it's crucial to build up a rapport with people. Which is why I tend to vocalize my &quot;hey, nice shoes&quot; thoughts and ask people about their kids and complain about the Patriots secondary. <br /><br />You just have to be careful... because if you think their shoes are ugly (or their shoes are boring loafers, so it makes no sense to compliment them) or you don't really care at all about sports, it's likely to come across as disingenuous. Especially if you have a tendency to rub people the wrong way. <br /><br />I've also gotten very good at telling people &quot;no&quot; while leaving them with the impression that I'm being extremely helpful. There's a bit of an art to it, but it mostly involves giving them other options and being very firm with them. <br /><br />I'm a work in progress (aren't we all?). I just got a bit snippy with a guy in the office who tends to be rather vociferously wrong about things. I got a little too vociferous and telling him that he was incorrect. He did come back and say &quot;oh, yeah, you were right&quot; but I still probably came off as a jerk in the way I said it. It's something that I'm working on.<br /><br />My mantra these days is, &quot;I don't care about being right. I care about being effective.&quot; You can have all of the facts on your side, but people will still make the wrong decision if you tick them off or make the wrong argument.

              

              
              
