        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Thanks, Hopers. That clarifies.<br /><br />Pastor, it helps if you think of personal items as another aspect of your project. Project stakeholders (other engineers, upper management, customers) are resources. Convincing project stakeholders is another set of tasks equally important to all of your technical items. To offer an example, a project to open a datacenter might have the following high-level tasks:<br />-Confirm physical structure: raised floor strength, security, fire suppression, etc.<br />-Acquire electrical circuits to provide sufficient power.<br />-Purchase server hardware and racks.<br />-Reserve 150 man-hours for physical installation.<br />-Reserver 200 man-hours for server configuration.<br /><br />A good engineer will thinks of these things. But a good project manager has to add a few items:<br />-Present project proposal to upper management. Obtain signed approval from a project sponsor.<br />-Verify working schedule for human resources in the last 2 bullet points. Contact their supervisors.<br />-Consult with other engineers about their projects. Offer help when possible.<br />-Clarify the project's benefit to co-workers and first-line supervisors.<br />-Request technical input from team members.<br /><br />Each of these are social, personal, or &quot;soft&quot; skills that are vital to your career. If you think of them as just schmoozing or &quot;office politics,&quot; you'll never get a handle on it. If you view them as just another engineering task; if you put &quot;Get that jerk Gary to sign off on this&quot; at the same level &quot;Make sure they installed enough cabling&quot;; then you'll be fine.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
